  --- Maven
  ="true"
            class="octicon octicon-link">  Download
           
  
           
                Packages
           
  
           If you are using MAVEN, add this entry to your POM file: 
  
            
  &lt;dependency&gt;
      &lt;groupId&gt;org.codehaus.janino&lt;/groupId&gt;
      &lt;artifactId&gt;janino&lt;/artifactId&gt;
      &lt;version&gt;***&lt;/version&gt;
  &lt;/dependency&gt;  
  
           
   
       org.codehaus.janino   
       janino<
  
  --- janino
   
   
     
       
       
       Janino by janino-compiler 
  
       
       
        
  
        
        
        
       </script
  
  --- commons-compiler
          
             
              Download  the latest version of
              "janino- version .jar" .
             
             
              Download  the same version of
              "commons-compiler- version .jar" .
             
             Put the two JAR files on your classpath. 
           
  
           
                Security / integrity
           
  
           
            All packages are signed with one of these PGP keys. Make sure to check the package 
  
  --- ExpressionEvaluator
            get you tooltip JAVADOC and source level debugging into the JANINO libraries.
           
  
           Use one of the features, e.g. the "expression evaluator", in your program: 
  
            
  import org.codehaus.janino.*;
  
  ExpressionEvaluator ee = new ExpressionEvaluator();
  ee.cook("3 + 4");
  System.out.println(ee.evaluate()); // Prints "7".  
  
           Compile, run, ... be happy! 
  
           
                Examples
           
  
           
            The <a
            href="https://github.com/janino-compiler/janino/blob/master/commons-compiler/src/main/java/org/codehaus/commons/c
  
  --- SimpleCompiler
  re> 
  
           
                Janino as a Simple
            Compiler
           
  
           
            The  SimpleCompiler  compiles a single .java file ("compilation unit").
            Opposed to normal Java compilation, that compilation unit may declare  more than one  public type.
           
          
           Example: 
  
            
  // This is file "Hello.java", but it could have any name.
  
  public
  class Foo {
  
      public static void
      main(String[] args) {
          new Bar().meth();
      }
  }
  
  public
  class Bar {
  
      public void
     
  
  --- ScriptEvaluator
   id="janino-as-a-script-evaluator" class="anchor" href="#janino-as-a-script-evaluator"
            aria-hidden="true">   Janino as a Script
            Evaluator
           
  
           
            Analogously to the expression evaluator, a ScriptEvaluator API exists that compiles and processes a Java
            "block", i.e. the body of a method. If a return value other than "void" is defined, then the block must
            return a value of that type.
           
  
           
            As a special feature, it allows methods to be declared. The place and order of the method declarations is not
            relevant.
           
  
           Example: 
  
            
  package foo;
  
  impor
  
