\nSystem.out.println(ee.evaluate()); // Prints \"7\".  \n\n         Compile, run, ... be happy! \n\n         \n              Examples\n         \n\n         \n          The <a\n          href=\"https://github.com/janino-compiler/janino/blob/master/commons-compiler/src/main/java/org/codehaus/commons/c\n\n--- SimpleCompiler\nre> \n\n         \n              Janino as a Simple\n          Compiler\n         \n\n         \n          The  SimpleCompiler  compiles a single .java file (\"compilation unit\").\n          Opposed to normal Java compilation, that compilation unit may declare  more than one  public type.\n         \n        \n         Example: \n\n          \n// This is file \"Hello.java\", but it could have any name.\n\npublic\nclass Foo {\n\n    public static void\n    main(String[] args) {\n        new Bar().meth();\n    }\n}\n\npublic\nclass Bar {\n\n    public void\n   \n\n--- ScriptEvaluator\n id=\"janino-as-a-script-evaluator\" class=\"anchor\" href=\"#janino-as-a-script-evaluator\"\n          aria-hidden=\"true\">   Janino as a Script\n          Evaluator\n         \n\n         \n          Analogously to the expression evaluator, a ScriptEvaluator API exists that compiles and processes a Java\n          \"block\", i.e. the body of a method. If a return value other than \"void\" is defined, then the block must\n          return a value of that type.\n         \n\n         \n          As a special feature, it allows methods to be declared. The place and order of the method declarations is not\n          relevant.\n         \n\n         Example: \n\n          \npackage foo;\n\nimpor\n\n--- Ant\niv style=\"margin-bottom:8px\">\n            Janino is now \"Tee-ware\", which means that the applicable license is still BSD,\n            but you are free to\n             buy a fan t-shirt on Teespring \n            (one per CPU, or as many as you want 😉).\n           \n           \n            Support the software development and show your appreciation by purchas